			<h3>
				<img src="/images/ns-documentation/insignia.png" alt="Sprout insignia for Nightsprout." />
				<span>Chapter 2: Deactivating Your Front Page</span>
				<div>“We Don't Need This Thing”</div>
			</h3>
			<p>The front page isn't for everyone.  If you don't think you want to use it, or you don't want the Front Page to be the default main page of your blog, this is the section for you.  If you want to keep your Front Page, skip this section. </p>
			<p>For ease of use, we've overwritten a default setting for WordPress.  Usually, WordPress expects the default page to be the list of blog posts.  We have changed this to be our custom Front Page interface.  If you wish to undo this, it is simple, but it requires following these steps that act somewhat against the standard WordPress settings:</p>
			<ol>
			  <li>Click on the "Pages" menu item, and then the "Add New" sub-menu item inside of it.</li>
			  <li>Enter the Title as "Blog", or whatever you want your Blog section to be called.</li>
			  <li>In the "Page Attributes" section of this page, under the "Template" heading, click on the drop-down selector and then click on the "Blog" option.</li>
        <li>Save this page.  It will be your new front page.</li>
        <li>If you still wish to use the Nightsprout Front Page, just not as the default first page of your site, repeat steps 1-4, except name it appropriately and click on "Nightsprout Front Page" under the "Template" dropdown.</li>
			  <li>Click on the "Settings" menu item, and then the "Reading" sub-menu item inside of it.</li>
			  <li>Next to the "Front Page Displays" option on this page, click on the radio button next to "A static page"</li>
			  <li>Click on the drop-down next to "Front Page" and select the page you set up for your Blog.</li>
			  <li>If you set up a secondary page for your Nightsprout Front Page, select it in the drop down menu next to "Posts Page".</li>
		  </ol>
